\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{\numberline {B.1}Four-strategy scaling at a matched 20K-token budget}{20}{subsection.B.1}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {The headline scaling result (3-seed mean $\pm $ SD), underlying \Cref  {fig:scaling}.} Pass rate by strategy\nobreakspace  {}$\times $\nobreakspace  {}budget on 15 hard code tasks, Sonnet 4. S, L, and H are averaged over three independent seeds; R was run once (its seed-to-seed variation is small at temp\nobreakspace  {}0), at the sweep's budget partition (a more generous partition lifts R to $86.7\%$; see \Cref  {tab:reasoning-baseline}). S's small dip from $B{=}1$K (80.0\%) to $B{=}5$K (77.8\%) is within the $\pm 3.1$\,pp seed noise: pass@$N$ is non-decreasing in $N$ in expectation, but not on every finite sample. Reasoning-only and best-of-$N$ both saturate well below 100\%, while all three feedback-iterating strategies reach $\geq 97.8\%$ at $B{=}20$K (L hits 100\% on 2 of 3 seeds, H on all 3, so H is the only variant at a strict 100\% across seeds). H and L tie on pass rate within seed noise; what separates them is token efficiency and reliability (\Cref  {fig:efficiency}).\relax }}{20}{table.caption.44}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:scaling-curves}{{2}{20}{\textbf {The headline scaling result (3-seed mean $\pm $ SD), underlying \Cref {fig:scaling}.} Pass rate by strategy~$\times $~budget on 15 hard code tasks, Sonnet 4. S, L, and H are averaged over three independent seeds; R was run once (its seed-to-seed variation is small at temp~0), at the sweep's budget partition (a more generous partition lifts R to $86.7\%$; see \Cref {tab:reasoning-baseline}). S's small dip from $B{=}1$K (80.0\%) to $B{=}5$K (77.8\%) is within the $\pm 3.1$\,pp seed noise: pass@$N$ is non-decreasing in $N$ in expectation, but not on every finite sample. Reasoning-only and best-of-$N$ both saturate well below 100\%, while all three feedback-iterating strategies reach $\geq 97.8\%$ at $B{=}20$K (L hits 100\% on 2 of 3 seeds, H on all 3, so H is the only variant at a strict 100\% across seeds). H and L tie on pass rate within seed noise; what separates them is token efficiency and reliability (\Cref {fig:efficiency}).\relax }{table.caption.44}{}}
\newlabel{tab:scaling-curves@cref}{{[table][2][2147483647]2}{[1][20][]20}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{\numberline {B.2}Reasoning-only at a matched budget}{21}{subsection.B.2}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Reasoning-only at a matched budget vs.\ single-shot and the harness on the 15 hard code tasks. These are single-seed numbers (the Phase-1 reference seed, also used in \Cref  {tab:type-controls}); the 3-run aggregate is in \Cref  {tab:harness-headline} ($66.7 \pm 6.7$\% single-shot, $100.0 \pm 0.0$\% reviewed). \emph  {Reading the numbers:} single-shot on this seed is $11/15 = 73.3\%$ (the canonical 3-seed mean is $66.7\%$), and the reasoning value shown is the \emph  {thinking-heavy} partition ($86.7\%$). Two numeric coincidences of this small suite can mislead: $86.7\%$ here matches the oracle best-of-$N$ ceiling, and the \emph  {default}-partition reasoning ceiling ($73.3\%$, \Cref  {tab:scaling-curves}) matches this seed's single-shot; neither is the same run. Reasoning closes two-thirds of the harness's gain over single-shot, but stays 6.7\,pp short of the harness even at $1.57\times $ its token budget.\relax }}{21}{table.caption.45}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:reasoning-baseline}{{3}{21}{Reasoning-only at a matched budget vs.\ single-shot and the harness on the 15 hard code tasks. These are single-seed numbers (the Phase-1 reference seed, also used in \Cref {tab:type-controls}); the 3-run aggregate is in \Cref {tab:harness-headline} ($66.7 \pm 6.7$\% single-shot, $100.0 \pm 0.0$\% reviewed). \emph {Reading the numbers:} single-shot on this seed is $11/15 = 73.3\%$ (the canonical 3-seed mean is $66.7\%$), and the reasoning value shown is the \emph {thinking-heavy} partition ($86.7\%$). Two numeric coincidences of this small suite can mislead: $86.7\%$ here matches the oracle best-of-$N$ ceiling, and the \emph {default}-partition reasoning ceiling ($73.3\%$, \Cref {tab:scaling-curves}) matches this seed's single-shot; neither is the same run. Reasoning closes two-thirds of the harness's gain over single-shot, but stays 6.7\,pp short of the harness even at $1.57\times $ its token budget.\relax }{table.caption.45}{}}
\newlabel{tab:reasoning-baseline@cref}{{[table][3][2147483647]3}{[1][20][]21}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{\numberline {B.3}Feedback-channel control on a fixed code suite}{21}{subsection.B.3}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces Feedback-channel controls on 15 hard code tasks (Sonnet 4 proposer and reviewer), underlying \Cref  {fig:typecontrol}. Each row is a single seed. ``SS'' is that seed's single-shot pass rate (it varies by row), and ``Reviewed'' is the ceiling after that seed's harness run. The three SS values (10/15 and 11/15) are draws from the same single-shot distribution behind \Cref  {tab:harness-headline}'s 3-run mean of $66.7 \pm 6.7$\% (within $\pm 1$\,SD of 10/15). Since SS varies by row, the comparison that matters is the \emph  {reviewed} ceiling: execution reaches 14/15, critique and critique+linter reach 13/15 ($+6.7$\,pp), \emph  {and} execution is ${\sim }2.5\times $ more token-efficient ($2{,}643$ vs.\ ${\sim }7{,}100$ tokens/task, 1.53 vs.\ 2.07 iterations). The one task no control row recovers is \texttt  {code\_011} (CJK text wrapping); the full harness at $B{=}20$K recovers it on all three seeds (\Cref  {tab:scaling-curves}), which is why the headline reviewed rate is a strict $100\%$ (\Cref  {tab:harness-headline}) while this leaner single-seed control caps at $14/15$.\relax }}{21}{table.caption.46}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:type-controls}{{4}{21}{Feedback-channel controls on 15 hard code tasks (Sonnet 4 proposer and reviewer), underlying \Cref {fig:typecontrol}. Each row is a single seed. ``SS'' is that seed's single-shot pass rate (it varies by row), and ``Reviewed'' is the ceiling after that seed's harness run. The three SS values (10/15 and 11/15) are draws from the same single-shot distribution behind \Cref {tab:harness-headline}'s 3-run mean of $66.7 \pm 6.7$\% (within $\pm 1$\,SD of 10/15). Since SS varies by row, the comparison that matters is the \emph {reviewed} ceiling: execution reaches 14/15, critique and critique+linter reach 13/15 ($+6.7$\,pp), \emph {and} execution is ${\sim }2.5\times $ more token-efficient ($2{,}643$ vs.\ ${\sim }7{,}100$ tokens/task, 1.53 vs.\ 2.07 iterations). The one task no control row recovers is \texttt {code\_011} (CJK text wrapping); the full harness at $B{=}20$K recovers it on all three seeds (\Cref {tab:scaling-curves}), which is why the headline reviewed rate is a strict $100\%$ (\Cref {tab:harness-headline}) while this leaner single-seed control caps at $14/15$.\relax }{table.caption.46}{}}
\newlabel{tab:type-controls@cref}{{[table][4][2147483647]4}{[1][21][]21}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{\numberline {B.4}Single-agent loop vs.\ proposer--reviewer harness}{21}{subsection.B.4}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces Three interaction-strategy variants at $B{=}20$K on the 15 hard code tasks, all using execution feedback; underlying \Cref  {fig:efficiency}. Pass rate is within seed noise (sign-test $p{>}0.6$ on the H--L comparison). The harness wins on \emph  {token efficiency} (1{,}029 vs.\ 1{,}431 L vs.\ 1{,}416 IAD mean output tokens) and on \emph  {seed variance} (zero across three seeds for H, while L hit 100\% in 2 of 3 seeds and IAD was run for one seed only).\relax }}{21}{table.caption.47}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:LvsH}{{5}{21}{Three interaction-strategy variants at $B{=}20$K on the 15 hard code tasks, all using execution feedback; underlying \Cref {fig:efficiency}. Pass rate is within seed noise (sign-test $p{>}0.6$ on the H--L comparison). The harness wins on \emph {token efficiency} (1{,}029 vs.\ 1{,}431 L vs.\ 1{,}416 IAD mean output tokens) and on \emph {seed variance} (zero across three seeds for H, while L hit 100\% in 2 of 3 seeds and IAD was run for one seed only).\relax }{table.caption.47}{}}
\newlabel{tab:LvsH@cref}{{[table][5][2147483647]5}{[1][21][]21}}
